title: Average radiative capture cross sections for 7- to 170-keV neutrons.

x4codes.hlp: Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States of America

x4freetext: Curves

flag.hlp: Reference to related data compiled in another entry

x4freetext: another
similar experiment.
Average radiative capture cross sections for 7- to
170-keV neutrons.

x4codes.hlp: Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States of America

x4freetext: The ORNL 3-MV Van de Graaff accelerator
The neutrons were produced by using the
7Li(p,n) and
T(p,n) reactions with thick targets and
the proton energy adjusted to cover the neutron
energy ranges 7-70 keV and 20-170 keV, respectively.
The natural element samples used to date have been 5-
to 7-inch diameter disks. Metals were used where
possible. Pressed oxides and lead salts in thin
(0.001 in.) evacuated iron cans were used when
necessary. The sample thickness was chosen to give
1/E attenuation for about 150-keV gamma rays, and to
limit the neutron scattering to a few percent.
Fast (nano-second) time-of-flight techniques.
Time spectra were obtained for the various samples,
with an indium (standard) sample being run approxim.
every fourth time, or about once every 15 minutes.
Liquid scintillator tank. The liquid
scintillator consists of double-distilled xylene
containing 4-5 g/liter p-terphenyl and 0.02 g/liter
2, 5-di-(biphenyl)-oxazole.
Tables from the author in pdf-files.
Translated from SCISRS
converted to REACTION formalism
deleted subentry 73, duplicate of 74.
SD:Updated to new date formats,lower case.
corrected according to last EXFOR rules and Dict.
BIB update. In Subent 034 data value at 175 eV deleted
Subent 106 was added.
OS. Uncertainties in sub.61 corrected

x4freetext: Considerable effort was therefore expended in
determining the shape of the indium capture cross
section relative to the shape of the total
absorption cross section of U-235 above 100 keV, and
relative to the shape of the 10B(n,alpha1+gamma)7Li
cross section below 140 keV.
For this goal additional experiments were made
(see description in PR,122,182,1961).
The absolute value of the indium capture
cross section was normalized to its values for
threshold neutrons (30 and 65 keV) (see Subent 106)
MONITOR corrected.

x4freetext: The weighted indium cross section resulting from
normalization at 30 keV was defined. (see REL-REF)
* The capture cross section of indium at 65 keV was
obtained by measuring the ratio of the 65 to 30 keV
cross sections.
* The indium capture cross section at 167 keV was
determined by normalizing the relative indium cross
section versus neutron energy curve at 30 and 65 keV
and reading the value as measured by the shape of the
U-235 absorption cross section.

flag.hlp: Reference to related data compiled in another entry

x4freetext: The best five of these measurements, with their
standard deviations, were used to provide normalization
for the present experiment in the following manner:
The capture tank measurements of the shapes of the
five cross sections as a function of neutron energy
were used to extend the spherical shell cross
sections to 30 keV. Then shell transmission
measurements compared with capture tank results.
